content.solution_latex:
We do some simplification, taking advantage of the fact that $n! = n\cdot (n-1)!$: \begin{align*}
\frac{9!\cdot 5!\cdot 2!}{8!\cdot 6!} &= \frac{9\cdot 8! \cdot 5! \cdot 2}{8!\cdot 6\cdot 5!}\\
&= \frac{9\cdot 2}{6}\\
&= \boxed{3}.
\end{align*}

This simplifies nicely because $5!$ divides both $6!$ and $7!$ evenly:


\begin{align*}
\frac{6! + 7!}{5!} &=\frac{6!}{5!} + \frac{7!}{5!}\\&= 6 + 6 \cdot 7\\
&= 6 \cdot 8 \\
&= \boxed{48}
\end{align*}

Cancel before multiplying: \begin{align*}
\frac{14!}{5!9!}&=\frac{14\cdot13\cdot12\cdot11\cdot10\cdot9!}{5\cdot4\cdot3\cdot2\cdot9!} \\
&= \frac{14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11 \cdot 10}{5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2} \\
&= \frac{14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11}{4 \cdot 3} \\
&= 14 \cdot 13 \cdot 11 \\
&= \boxed{2002}
\end{align*}

We factor and rearrange the terms in the factorials:

\begin{align*}
\frac{3\cdot 5! + 15\cdot 4!}{6!} &= \frac{3\cdot 5! + 3\cdot 5!}{6!} \\
&= \frac{2\cdot 3 \cdot 5!}{6!} \\
&= \frac{6!}{6!} \\
&= \boxed{1}
\end{align*}

We can separate the fraction to get $\frac{6!}{5!} +\frac{4!}{5!}$. We can then simplify the quotient of factorials:

\begin{align*}
\frac{6!}{5!} +\frac{4!}{5!} &= \frac{6\cdot5!}{5!} +\frac{4!}{5\cdot4!}\\
&=6+\frac15\\
&=\boxed{6\frac15}.
\end{align*}

Of the 5 boxes with pencils, 2 have pens also, so $5-2=3$ have pencils only.  Similarly, $4-2 =2$ of the boxes have pens only:


[asy]
unitsize(0.05cm);
label("Pencils", (2,74));
label("Pens", (80,74));
draw(Circle((30,45), 22));
draw(Circle((58, 45), 22));
label("$2$", (44, 45));
label(scale(0.8)*"$3$",(28,58));
label(scale(0.8)*"$2$",(63,58));
[/asy]

That gives us $3+2+2=7$ boxes with pens, pencils, or both.  This leaves $10-7 = \boxed{3}$ with neither.

