Fourteen white cubes are put together to form the figure on the right.  The complete surface of the figure, including the bottom, is painted red.  The figure is then separated into individual cubes.  How many of the individual cubes have exactly four red faces?

[asy]
size(150);
pair a=(1,0),b=(0,1),c=(0.45,0.4);

void drawcube(pair loc){
     filldraw(loc+b--loc--loc+a--loc+a+c--loc+a+b+c--loc+b+c--cycle,white);
     draw(loc+b--loc+a+b--loc+a+b+c^^loc+a+b--loc+a);
}

pair location[]={origin,b,a,2a,3a,3a+b,-c,3a-c,-2c,-2c+b,-2c+a,-2c+2a,-2c+3a,-2c+3a+b};

for(int i; i<14;++i){
   drawcube(location[i]);
}


[/asy]

$A$, $B$ and $C$ are circular regions as shown. There are 7 items in circle $C$. There are exactly 20 items in $A$ and 10 of those items are not in $B$. How many items are in $B$, but not in $C$?

[asy]
draw(Circle((0,0),50));
label("$A$",(39,39));
draw(Circle((10,-10),32));
label("$B$",(-16,16));
draw(Circle((5,-5),20));
label("$C$",(22,-22));
[/asy]

content.solution_latex:
We can simplify directly

\begin{align*}
2\left(\frac{7!}{3!4!}\right) &= 2\left(\frac{7\cdot 6 \cdot 5}{3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}\right) \\
&= \frac{7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5}{3 \cdot 1} \\
&= 7 \cdot 2 \cdot 5 \\
&= \boxed{70}
\end{align*}
